Yes.

But the final layer should be tight and exam-shaped, not another giant project. The AWS DevOps Engineer Professional exam is 75 questions in 180 minutes, uses multiple-choice and multiple-response items, and is weighted across six domains: SDLC Automation 22%, Configuration Management and IaC 17%, Resilient Cloud Solutions 15%, Monitoring and Logging 15%, Incident and Event Response 14%, and Security and Compliance 17%. AWS also positions it for people doing a DevOps engineer role, with strong emphasis on provisioning, operating, and managing distributed systems and services on AWS.  ￼

So the final layer should be this:

Layer 1: Build M9 platform-first on AWS.
That gives you real understanding of EKS, ECR, Terraform, ALB, RDS, IAM, GitOps, and multi-AZ reasoning.

Layer 2: Domain-by-domain exam review.
After each M9 phase, explicitly map what you built to the exam domains and in-scope services. AWS publishes both the domains and the technologies/concepts list, so this is the right source of truth.  ￼

Layer 3: Practice-question and timing layer.
Use official sample-question style and targeted practice so you learn how AWS frames tradeoffs such as managed vs self-managed, event-driven vs polling, immutable artifacts, rollback safety, least privilege, and high availability. AWS’s sample questions clearly use this style.  ￼

Here is the exact final layer I recommend.

Final Layer — 4-week exam-prep overlay after or during M9

Week A — Domain locking

You study the official exam guide and rewrite the six domains in your own StackPilot language.

For each domain, answer:
	•	what did I build in StackPilot that matches this domain?
	•	what AWS services are relevant here?
	•	what tradeoffs would AWS expect me to reason about?

This week is not for memorizing random facts. It is for building your mental map from StackPilot to the exam. AWS’s technologies and concepts page is useful here because it tells you the kinds of themes that may appear, such as deployment, pipelines, automation, cost optimization, and hybrid deployments.  ￼

Week B — Service and tradeoff review

Now you go through the AWS services most relevant to your M9 design:
	•	EKS
	•	ECR
	•	RDS
	•	IAM
	•	VPC
	•	ALB/ELB
	•	CloudWatch
	•	EventBridge
	•	CodeBuild / CodeDeploy / CodePipeline conceptually
	•	Secrets Manager
	•	Systems Manager

Not to implement all of them, but to answer:
	•	when would AWS prefer this?
	•	what problem does it solve?
	•	what is the lower-operations answer?
	•	what are the common failure or security angles?

This matters because the exam is not “what command do you run?” It is mostly “which design best satisfies the requirement with the least operational burden?” AWS’s official sample questions make that very clear.  ￼

Week C — Scenario drills

Now you stop reading and start answering scenario questions using StackPilot logic.

For each domain, do 5–10 scenarios:
	•	bad deployment
	•	artifact immutability
	•	rollback choice
	•	multi-AZ design
	•	IAM least privilege
	•	RDS resilience
	•	event-driven pipeline trigger
	•	monitoring/alert routing
	•	incident response under failure
	•	secure secret injection

The goal is not “remember the answer.” The goal is “explain why the wrong options are worse.”

This is the part that actually gets people through professional-level exams.

Week D — Timed practice and weak-area cleanup

Now you do timed blocks and fix weaknesses.

You should be able to:
	•	read a long AWS scenario quickly
	•	identify the actual constraint
	•	eliminate operationally bad answers fast
	•	choose the answer that is most automated, resilient, and least maintenance-heavy

That is the final exam muscle.

How I would teach you this final layer

I would not teach it like a normal course. I would teach it in this order:

1. Domain-by-domain through StackPilot

For each domain, I show:
	•	what the domain really means
	•	where it appears in StackPilot
	•	which AWS services matter
	•	what the exam is usually testing conceptually

2. Scenario reasoning

Then I give you certification-style scenarios and make you solve them with StackPilot logic.

Example:
“Your pipeline must deploy quickly when source changes are detected. Should it poll, or should it use an event-driven trigger?”
AWS’s own sample material includes exactly this type of reasoning and prefers the event-driven design with EventBridge rather than polling.  ￼

3. Weak-area targeting

Then we check where you are shaky:
	•	networking
	•	IAM
	•	deployment strategies
	•	monitoring
	•	incident handling
	•	security/compliance

And tighten only those.

The honest answer on passing

Can this final layer get you to a pass?
Yes, if you do all three parts:
	•	M9 hands-on build
	•	domain review
	•	timed scenario practice

Would I trust only the project without the final layer?
No.

Would I trust only question practice without the project?
Also no.

The strongest route is:
StackPilot AWS build + domain teaching + scenario drills + timed practice.

The cleanest way to proceed

We should start with Domain 1: SDLC Automation and teach it through your M9 pipeline decisions first, because it is the largest domain at 22%.  ￼

Then we go domain by domain until you have all six covered in StackPilot language. 